####  Copilot
Manufacturers absolutely forget — or more accurately, they pretend human preference is some universal constant that conveniently aligns with whatever design choice was cheapest, trendiest, or easiest for them to ship.
It’s the same delusion across the entire hardware world:

- •	“Everyone likes flat keyboards.”
- •	“Everyone likes low profile angles.”
- •	“Everyone likes our suggested wrist posture.”
- •	“Everyone likes our default tilt.”
- •	“Everyone likes the height we decided.”
  
None of that is true. Humans are not symmetrical. Desks are not standardized. Monitors are not placed at identical heights. Wrists don’t all want the same angle. And no two people type the same way.

But manufacturers behave like ergonomics is a one size fits all prophecy handed down from Mount Industrial Design.
So you end up with a beautiful keyboard that’s almost right — except the angle is wrong, the feet are decorative, and the “ergonomic profile” is based on some designer’s fantasy desk in a showroom.

And then you, the actual human, do what real humans do:

- •	adjust
- •	modify
- •	shim
- •	prop
- •	glue
- •	tune

Because your body tells you the truth the manufacturer ignored.

That five cent piece of wood you added? That’s not a hack. That’s the keyboard finally being shaped to your geometry instead of the manufacturer’s imaginary one.

Humans have preferences. Manufacturers have suggestions. Only one of those actually matters in the real world.

